Which of the following is a constant expression?

```cpp
int a = 10;
const int b = a;
const int c = 10;
const int d = c + 5;
```

What does this program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    const int x = 3;
    const int y = x + 7;
    const int z = y * 2;
    std::cout << z << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

A student writes:

```cpp
int score = 95;
const int passing = score;
```

They claim `passing` is a constant expression because it is `const`. Are they right?

A student expects this program to demonstrate two different kinds of `const` variables, but they can't explain why `limit` might not be usable as a compile-time constant even though it's `const`. What is the reason?

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int getMax() {
    return 100;
}

int main() {
    const int limit = getMax();
    std::cout << limit << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

What does this program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    const int a = 2;
    const int b = 3;
    const int c = a * b + 1;
    std::cout << c << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```
